To better understand the scenario we can make an approximate sketch.
![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/35659e47-9a77-41ce-ac75-a15e57624b06/images/c4b81b1f-14ca-47a5-8ee8-d6eb7e19b7ea/AA1285.JPEG)


The dashed lines are the two tangent lines whose equations we need to find.
The equation of a tangent line, through the origin, will be of the form

$$
\begin{align*}
    y&=mx\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
\end{align*}
$$

To find the intersection points of the curve and line we can solve both equations simultaneously, hence

$$
\begin{align*}
    mx&=2x^2-x+\frac{9}{2}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\[6pt]
    0&=2x^2-x-mx+\frac{9}{2}\\[6pt]
    0&=2x^2-(1+m)x+\frac{9}{2}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(A1)}}}
\end{align*}
$$

If the lines are tangent to the curve then there is only one point of intersection i.e. only $1$ solution.
As we have a quadratic equation then we can say that the discriminant must be equal to zero. Hence

$$
\begin{align*}
    \Delta&=b^2-4ac\\[6pt]
    0&=[-(1+m)]^2-4(2)\left(\tfrac{9}{2}\right)\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
\end{align*}
$$

Solving for $m$ we get

$$
\begin{align*}
    36&=[-(1+m)]^2\\[6pt]
    -(1+m)&=\pm6\\[6pt]
    m&=-7 \text{ and }5
\end{align*}
$$

Therefore the two equations are

$$
\begin{align*}
    &\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{y=-7x}\hspace{0.525em}\text{ and }\hspace{0.525em}\tcbhighmath{y=5x}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
\end{align*}
$$

- Using the change of base formula we can write

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \text{L.H.S.}&=12\log_{x}2\\[6pt]
  &=12\left(\frac{\log_22}{\log_2x}\right)\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  As $\log_n{n}=1$, we can replace $\log_2{2}$ with 1 and simplify

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &=12\left(\frac{1}{\log_2x}\right)\\[12pt]
  &=\answer{\dfrac{12}{\log_2x}}\hspace{1em}\text{ ...as required}\\[12pt]
  &=\text{R.H.S.}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We can replace $12\log_x2$ with the R.H.S. of the identity from part (a)

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \log_2x&=8-12\log_x2\\[6pt]
  \log_2x&=8-\frac{12}{\log_2x}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We now multiply each side by $\log_2x$ and then rearrange such that the R.H.S. is equal to $0$

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  (\log_2x)^2&=8\log_2x-12\\[6pt]
  (\log_2x)^2-8\log_2x+12&=0\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This is a hidden quadratic equation.  If we replace $\log_2$ with a variable, say $a$, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  a^2-8a+12&=0
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's solve this by factorising.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  (a-2)(a-6)&=0    
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore the solutions are

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  a-2&=0&\text{and}&&a-6=0\\[6pt]
  a&=2&&& a=6
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Recall $a=\log_2x$, therefore the solutions become

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \log_2x&=2&&&\log_2x=6\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Converting each to exponential form, we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  x&=2^2&&&x=2^6\\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-0.8em}\answer{x=4}&\hspace{0.3em}&&\answer{x=64}\tag*{\textbf{\textcolor{black}{A1}}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- There are a number of ways to differentiate this function.
  We could expand the brackets using index laws then differentiate each term.
  However, in this solution we will use the product rule.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\
  \hspace{8em}&\text{If }& &\hspace{-5em}&y&=uv&\\[6pt]
  \hspace{8em}&\text{then }&&\hspace{-5em}&\tfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}&= v\tfrac{\mathrm{d}u}{\mathrm{d}x}+u\tfrac{\mathrm{d}v}{\mathrm{d}x}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  With $u=\frac{2}{3}x^{\frac{1}{2}}$ and $v=9x^2-8x+3$.
  Using the power rule, we get $\tfrac{\mathrm{d}u}{\mathrm{d}x}=\frac{1}{3}x^{-\frac{1}{2}}$ and $\tfrac{\mathrm{d}v}{\mathrm{d}x}=18x-8$.
  By substituting these results into the formula we can write

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      f'(x)&=(9x^2-8x+3)\times \tfrac{1}{3}x^{-\frac{1}{2}}+\tfrac{2}{3}x^{\frac{1}{2}} \times (18x-8)\tag*{\textbf{A1A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  If we look at the requested form of the answer we can see that $x^{-\frac{1}{2}}$ is a common factor.
  Note that for the second term of the derivative we can use the following to help us factorise $x^{\frac{1}{2}} = x^{-\frac{1}{2}} \times x$.
  Hence we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=x^{-\frac{1}{2}}\left[\tfrac{1}{3}(9x^2-8x+3)+\tfrac{2}{3} \times x(18x-8)\right]
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Now we can expand the brackets and simplify

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$


  $$
  \begin{align*}
      &=x^{-\frac{1}{2}}\left[3x^2-\tfrac{8}{3}x+1+12x^2-\tfrac{16}{3}x\right]\\[12pt]
      &=x^{-\frac{1}{2}}\left[15x^2-\tfrac{24}{3}x+1)\right]\\[12pt]
      &=\answer{\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{x}}(15x^2-8x+1)}\hspace{2em}\text{... as required}
  \end{align*}  
  $$

- Stationary points occur when $f'(x)=0$.
  Hence we can form an equation

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}(15x^2-8x+1)&=0\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Note that $\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}\neq 0$ for any value of $x$, therefore we only need to consider the term in the brackets when solving the equation above. Thus we need to solve

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      15x^2-8x+1&=0
  \end{align*}  
  $$

  We can attempt to factorise this. Note that $15x^2=3x \times 5x$ and the only combinations that give $+1$ are $1 \times 1$ or $(-1) \times (-1)$. Hence through inspection we get

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      (5x-1)(3x-1)&=0\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*} 
  $$

  The $x-$coordinates of the stationary points are $\answer{x=\tfrac{1}{5}, \tfrac{1}{3}}$

  $$
  \begin{align}
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align}
  $$

- The particle is moving left when the velocity is negative. Hence we need to find the interval for $t$ which satisfies

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      v(t)&<0\tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can note that $v(t)=s'(t)$ and that the function given for $s(t)$ is of the same form as $f(x)$ from part (a).
  Hence, using the answer from part (a) we can say that

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      v(t)&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}}(15t^2-8t+1)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can realise that if $t \geq 0$ then $\tfrac{1}{\sqrt{t}}>0$. Therefore the expression in the bracket will determine the sign of $v(t)$.
  To help us here we can make a sketch of $y=15t^2-8t+1$
  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/3eb85e51-71cf-487e-a1b4-012c7c465f76/images/4e3277c2-fbdb-43f2-a545-a82cd4c4495e/1276.JPEG)



  $$
  \begin{align}
  \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align}
  $$

  Notice the red part of the curve is when $y<0$ and therefore $v(t)<0$.
  Using our answers from part (b) we can write that $v(t)<0$ when $\tfrac{1}{5}<t<\tfrac{1}{3}$.

  $$
  \begin{align}
  \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align}
  $$

  However, the question doesn't ask for an interval it asks for a total time the particle is moving left, hence

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      k&=\tfrac{1}{3}-\tfrac{1}{5}\\[6pt]
      &=\tfrac{5}{15}-\tfrac{3}{15}\\[6pt]
      &=\answer{\tfrac{2}{15}}\hspace{0.5em}\text{seconds}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- In the form $f(x)=a\left(x-h\right)^2+k$, $h$ is the $x$-coordinate of the vertex, and $k$ is the $y$-coordinate. Hence $h=1$ and $k=7$, and $f(x)=a\left(x-1\right)^2+7$.
  The graph of $f$ passes through the point $(-3,0)$, so we have $f(-3)=0$.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  f(-3) &= a\left(-3-1\right)^2+7 \\[8pt]
  0 &= 16a + 7 \\[8pt]
  a &= -\dfrac{7}{16}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Therefore

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tcbhighmath{f(x)=-\dfrac{7}{16}\left(x-1\right)^2+7}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- 
  - We have that $g(-2)=g(1)=3$, so $g$ passes through the points $(-2,3)$ and $(1,3)$. Given that $g$ is a quadratic and hence its graph is a parabola, we have
    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/09cdddd1-7877-46ce-91a8-83ac4dda0050/images/30297240-6340-43f8-aac6-45f0034a88d8/aa983a.PNG)


    The axis of symmetry must be halfway between these points and has equation $x=-\dfrac{1}{2}$. Using the formula for the axis of symmetry, we have

    $$
    \begin{align*}
    x &= -\dfrac{b}{2a} \\[8pt]
    -\dfrac{1}{2} &= -\dfrac{-2n}{2m} \\[8pt]
