- If $g$ and $h$ always have two distinct points of intersection, then the equation $g(x)=h(x)$ must have two unique solutions. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  g(x) &= h(x) \\[8pt]
  mx^2-2nx+\dfrac{2n^2}{m} &= nx + 1 \\[8pt]
  mx^2 - 3nx + \dfrac{2n^2}{m} -1 &= 0
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We can use the discriminant to check the number of solutions.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \Delta &= b^2 - 4ac \\[8pt]
  &= (-3n)^2 - 4(m)\left(\dfrac{2n^2}{m} -1\right)\\[8pt]
  &=(-3n)^2 - 4(m)\left(\dfrac{2n^2}{m} -1\right) \\[8pt]
  &=9n^2 - 8n^2 + 4m \\[8pt]
  &=n^2 + 4m 
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Given that $m \in \mathbb{R}^+$, $4m>0$. $n^2 \geq 0$. Hence $\Delta>0$. Thus
  $\tcbhighmath{\text{The graphs of $h$ and $g$ have two distinct points of intersection for all $m \in \mathbb{R}^+$ and $n \in \mathbb{R}$.}}$

- By completing the square, we can rewrite $f(x)$ into the desired form

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      f(x)&=\tfrac{1}{4}(x^2-4x)+3\\[6pt]
      &=\tfrac{1}{4}[(x-2)^2-2^2]+3\tag*{\textbf{(M1)A1}}\\[6pt]
      &=\tfrac{1}{4}(x-2)^2-1+3\\[6pt]
      &\hspace{0.2em}\answer{=\tfrac{1}{4}(x-2)^2+2}\tag*{\textbf{A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- We can use the inverse power rule to integrate the function

  $$
  \begin{align*}
      \int f(x)\,dx&=\int {\left[\tfrac{1}{4}(x-2)^2+2\right]}\,dx\\[12pt]
      &=\answer{\tfrac{1}{12}(x-2)^3+2x+C} \tag*{\textbf{A1A1}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

